data.name: Mr. Mime

attacks.name: Look-Alike Show
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand. You may use the effect of a Supporter card you find there as the effect of this attack.

attacks.name: Eerie Wave
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Confused.

data.flavorText: The broadness of its hands may be no coincidence—many scientists believe its palms became enlarged specifically for pantomiming.

data.name: Marill

attacks.name: Ball Roll
attacks.text: Flip a coin until you get tails. This attack does 10 damage for each heads.

data.flavorText: The fur on its body naturally repels water. It can stay dry even when it plays in the water.

data.name: Azumarill

attacks.name: Play Rough
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 more damage.

attacks.name: Power Tackle
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.flavorText: Its long ears are superb sensors. It can distinguish the movements of things in water and tell what they are.

data.name: Girafarig

attacks.name: Psychic Assault
attacks.text: This attack does 10 more damage for each damage counter on your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Girafarig's tail has a small head. It instinctively bites at any foe that approaches the Pokémon from behind.

data.name: Latias

attacks.name: Allure
attacks.text: Draw 2 cards.

data.flavorText: It communicates using telepathy. Its body is covered in down that refracts light to make it invisible.

data.name: Bronzor

attacks.name: Mirror Attack
attacks.text: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is a Psychic Pokémon, this attack does 30 more damage.

data.flavorText: Ancient people believed that the pattern on Bronzor's back contained a mysterious power.

data.name: Bronzong

attacks.name: Evolution Jammer
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, they can't play any Pokémon from their hand to evolve their Pokémon.

data.flavorText: In ages past, this Pokémon was revered as a bringer of rain. It was found buried in the ground.

data.name: Solosis

attacks.name: Surprise Attack
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

data.flavorText: It communicates with others telepathically. Its body is encapsulated in liquid, but if it takes a heavy blow, the liquid will leak out.

data.name: Duosion

attacks.name: Double Trick
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 30 damage for each heads.

data.flavorText: Its psychic power can supposedly cover a range of more than half a mile—but only if its two brains can agree with each other.

data.name: Reuniclus

attacks.name: Summoning Gate
attacks.text: Look at the top 8 cards of your deck. You may put any number of Pokémon you find there onto your Bench. Shuffle the other cards back into your deck.

attacks.name: Brain Shake
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Confused.

data.flavorText: While it could use its psychic abilities in battle, this Pokémon prefers to swing its powerful arms around to beat opponents into submission.

data.name: Elgyem

attacks.name: Hide
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from and effects of attacks done to this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: If this Pokémon stands near a TV, strange scenery will appear on the screen. That scenery is said to be from its home.

data.name: Beheeyem

attacks.name: Cosmic Beatdown
attacks.text: This attack does 20 damage for each of your Pokémon in play.

data.flavorText: Whenever a Beheeyem visits a farm, a Dubwool mysteriously disappears.

data.name: Cutiefly

attacks.name: Mini Drain
attacks.text: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Nectar and pollen are its favorite fare. You can find Cutiefly hovering around Gossifleur, trying to get some of Gossifleur's pollen.

data.name: Ribombee

attacks.name: Plentiful Pollen
attacks.text: During your next turn, if the Defending Pokémon is Knocked Out, take 2 more Prize cards.

data.flavorText: It makes pollen puffs from pollen and nectar. The puffs' effects depend on the type of ingredients and how much of each one is used.

data.name: Scream Tail

attacks.name: Supportive Singing
attacks.text: Heal 100 damage from 1 of your Benched Ancient Pokémon.

data.flavorText: There has been only one reported sighting of this Pokémon. It resembles a mysterious creature depicted in an old expedition journal.

data.name: Flutter Mane

abilities.name: Midnight Fluttering
abilities.text: As long as this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, your opponent's Active Pokémon has no Abilities, except for Midnight Fluttering.

attacks.name: Hex Hurl
attacks.text: Put 2 damage counters on your opponent's Benched Pokémon in any way you like.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon has characteristics similar to those of Flutter Mane, a creature mentioned in a certain book.

data.name: Iron Valiant

attacks.name: Calculation
attacks.text: Look at the top 4 cards of your deck and put them back in any order.

attacks.name: Majestic Sword
attacks.text: If you played a Future Supporter card from your hand during this turn, this attack does 100 more damage.

data.flavorText: It's possible that this is the object listed as Iron Valiant in a certain expedition journal.

data.name: Iron Valiant

attacks.name: Gemini Laser
attacks.text: This attack also does 20 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon. (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

attacks.name: Zen Blade
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't use Zen Blade.

data.flavorText: It's possible that this is the object listed as Iron Valiant in a certain expedition journal.

abilities.text: Attacks used by your Future Pokémon, except any Iron Crown ex, do 20 more damage to your opponent's Active Pokémon (before applying Weakness and Resistance).

attacks.name: Twin Shotels
attacks.text: This attack does 50 damage to 2 of your opponent's Pokémon. This attack's damage isn't affected by Weakness or Resistance, or by any effects on those Pokémon.

data.name: Meditite
data.flavorText: It meditates to heighten its inner energy and to float in the air. It eats one berry a day.

data.name: Medicham
data.flavorText: It elegantly avoids attacks with dance-like steps, then launches a devastating blow in the same motion.

data.name: Relicanth

abilities.name: Memory Dive
abilities.text: Each of your evolved Pokémon can use any attack from its previous Evolutions. (You still need the necessary Energy to use each attack.)

data.flavorText: Rock-hard scales and oil-filled swim bladders allow this Pokémon to survive the intense water pressure of the deep sea.

data.name: Drilbur

abilities.name: Dig Dig Dig
abilities.text: When you play this Pokémon from your hand onto your Bench during your turn, you may search your deck for up to 3 Basic Fighting Energy cards and discard them. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: It brings its claws together and whirls around at high speed before rushing toward its prey.

data.name: Excadrill

attacks.name: Wild Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 50 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: It's not uncommon for tunnels that appear to have formed naturally to actually be a result of Excadrill's rampant digging.

data.name: Golett

attacks.name: Iron Defense
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks.

data.flavorText: They were sculpted from clay in ancient times. No one knows why, but some of them are driven to continually line up boulders.

data.name: Golurk

attacks.name: Iron Defense
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks.

attacks.name: Fighting Fist
attacks.text: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is a Pokémon ex or Pokémon V, this attack does 120 more damage.

data.flavorText: Artillery platforms built into the walls of ancient castles served as perches from which Golurk could fire energy beams.

data.name: Rockruff
data.flavorText: This Pokémon is very friendly when it's young. Its disposition becomes vicious once it matures, but it never forgets the kindness of its master.

data.name: Lycanroc

attacks.name: Turbo Edge
attacks.text: Attach up to 2 Basic Fighting Energy cards from your discard pile to your Benched Pokémon in any way you like.

data.flavorText: Lycanroc attacks its prey with its sharp claws and fangs. It loyally obeys the instructions of a Trainer it trusts.

data.name: Mudbray
data.flavorText: This Pokémon covers itself in mud that it has regurgitated. The mud won't dry out even if it's exposed to the sun for a long time.

data.name: Mudsdale

attacks.name: Mud Stock
attacks.text: Attach a Basic Fighting Energy card from your discard pile to each of your Benched Pokémon.

attacks.name: High Horsepower
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 40 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon has been treasured not just for its physical labor but also because it produces high-quality mud used for making pottery.

data.name: Rolycoly
data.flavorText: On sunny days, Rolycoly will come out onto grassy plains and roll around. Then it will eat the grass that gets tangled in its wheel-like leg.

data.name: Carkol

attacks.name: Knock Away
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 40 more damage.

data.flavorText: The temperature inside its body increases when it experiences strong emotions. It rolls around frantically while spewing flames.

data.name: Coalossal

attacks.name: Gatling Tar
attacks.text: This attack does 80 more damage for each Fire Energy attached to this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Cragalanche
attacks.text: Discard the top 2 cards of your opponent's deck.

data.flavorText: To intimidate its opponents, Coalossal will vigorously shake its body, scattering coal from its smoldering back.

data.name: Great Tusk

attacks.name: Wrathful Charge
attacks.text: If your Benched Pokémon have any damage counters on them, this attack does 80 more damage.

data.flavorText: Sightings of this Pokémon have occurred in recent years. The name Great Tusk was taken from a creature listed in a certain book.

data.name: Great Tusk

attacks.name: Land Collapse
attacks.text: Discard the top card of your opponent's deck. If you played an Ancient Supporter card from your hand during this turn, discard 3 more cards in this way.

data.flavorText: Sightings of this Pokémon have occurred in recent years. The name Great Tusk was taken from a creature listed in a certain book.

data.name: Sandy Shocks

attacks.name: Magnetic Burst
attacks.text: If you have 3 or more Energy in play, this attack does 70 more damage. This attack's damage isn't affected by Weakness.

data.flavorText: No records exist of this Pokémon being caught. Data is lacking, but the Pokémon's traits match up with a creature shown in an expedition journal.

rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Repulsor Axe
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, if this Pokémon is damaged by an attack (even if it is Knocked Out), put 8 damage counters on the Attacking Pokémon.

attacks.name: Power Stomp
attacks.text: Discard 2 Energy from this Pokémon.

data.name: Ekans

attacks.name: Poison Blend
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Confused and Poisoned.

data.flavorText: The older it gets, the longer it grows. At night, it wraps its long body around tree branches to rest.

data.name: Arbok

attacks.name: Panic Poison
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Burned, Confused, and Poisoned.

data.flavorText: The pattern on its belly appears to be a frightening face. Weak foes will flee just at the sight of the pattern.

data.name: Gastly

attacks.name: Mysterious Beam
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, discard an Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It wraps its opponent in its gas-like body, slowly weakening its prey by poisoning it through the skin.

data.name: Haunter

attacks.name: Super Poison Breath
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

data.flavorText: It likes to lurk in the dark and tap shoulders with a gaseous hand. Its touch causes endless shuddering.

rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

abilities.name: Gnawing Curse
abilities.text: Whenever your opponent attaches an Energy card from their hand to 1 of their Pokémon, put 2 damage counters on that Pokémon.

attacks.name: Tricky Steps
attacks.text: You may move an Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon to 1 of their Benched Pokémon.

data.name: Mightyena

attacks.name: Kick Away
attacks.text: Switch out your opponent's Active Pokémon to the Bench. (Your opponent chooses the new Active Pokémon.)

data.flavorText: It will always obey the commands of a skilled Trainer. Its behavior arises from its living in packs in ancient times.

data.name: Poochyena

attacks.name: Gnaw Off
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 more damage.

data.flavorText: A Pokémon with a persistent nature, it chases its chosen prey until the prey becomes exhausted.

data.name: Sableye

attacks.name: Damage Collection
attacks.text: You may move any number of damage counters from your opponent's Benched Pokémon to their Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It dwells in the darkness of caves. It uses its sharp claws to dig up gems to nourish itself.

Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.
Tera: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).

attacks.name: Dirty Beam
attacks.text: This attack also does 30 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon. (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

data.name: Roaring Moon

attacks.name: Vengeance Fletching
attacks.text: This attack does 10 more damage for each Ancient card in your discard pile.

data.flavorText: It is possible that this is the creature listed as Roaring Moon in an expedition journal that still holds many mysteries.

data.name: Forretress

attacks.name: Spike Cannon
attacks.text: Flip 3 coins. This attack does 30 damage for each heads.

attacks.name: Steel Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 40 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: Its entire body is shielded by a steel-hard shell. What lurks inside this shell is a total mystery.

data.name: Scizor ex

attacks.name: Steel Wing
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes 50 less damage from attacks (after applying Weakness and Resistance).

attacks.name: Cross Breaker
attacks.text: Discard up to 2 Metal Energy from this Pokémon. This attack does 120 damage for each card you discarded in this way.

data.name: Mawile

attacks.name: Invite and Strike
attacks.text: Switch in 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon to the Active Spot. This attack does 30 damage to the new Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It uses its docile-looking face to lull foes into complacency, then bites with its huge, relentless jaws.

data.name: Metang

abilities.name: Metal Maker
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may look at the top 4 cards of your deck and attach any number of Basic Metal Energy cards you find there to your Pokémon in any way you like. Shuffle the other cards and put them on the bottom of your deck.

data.flavorText: Two Beldum have become stuck together via their own magnetic forces. With two brains, the resulting Metang has doubled psychic powers.

data.name: Meltan
data.flavorText: It dissolves and eats metal. Circulating liquid metal within its body is how it generates energy.

data.name: Beldum

attacks.name: Iron Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 10 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: From its rear, Beldum emits a magnetic force that rapidly pulls opponents in. They get skewered on Beldum's sharp claws.

data.name: Metagross

attacks.name: Meteor Mash
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon's Meteor Mash attack does 60 more damage (before applying Weakness and Resistance).

attacks.name: Luster Blast
attacks.text: Discard 2 Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Because the magnetic powers of these Pokémon get stronger in freezing temperatures, Metagross living on snowy mountains are full of energy.

data.name: Melmetal
data.flavorText: At the end of its life-span, Melmetal will rust and fall apart. The small shards left behind will eventually be reborn as Meltan.

data.name: Iron Treads

abilities.name: Dual Core
abilities.text: As long as this Pokémon has a Future Booster Energy Capsule attached, it is Fighting and Metal type.

attacks.name: Wheel Pass
attacks.text: Move an Energy from this Pokémon to 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Sightings of this Pokémon have occurred in recent years. It resembles a mysterious object described in an old expedition journal.

data.name: Raging Bolt ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Burst Roar
attacks.text: Discard your hand and draw 6 cards.

attacks.name: Bellowing Thunder
attacks.text: You may discard any amount of Basic Energy from your Pokémon. This attack does 70 damage for each card you discarded in this way.

data.name: Koraidon

attacks.name: Primordial Beatdown
attacks.text: This attack does 30 damage for each of your Ancient Pokémon in play.

attacks.name: Shred
attacks.text: This attack's damage isn't affected by any effects on your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: This seems to be the Winged King mentioned in an old expedition journal. It was said to have split the land with its bare fists.

data.name: Lickitung

attacks.name: Tongue Pull
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand. Put up to 2 Basic Pokémon you find there onto your opponent's Bench.

data.flavorText: If this Pokémon's sticky saliva gets on you and you don't clean it off, an intense itch will set in. The itch won't go away, either.

data.name: Koraidon ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Retribution Strike
attacks.text: This attack does 10 more damage for each damage counter on this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Kaiser Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 60 damage to itself.

data.name: Miraidon

attacks.name: Peak Acceleration
attacks.text: Search your deck for up to 2 Basic Energy cards and attach them to your Future Pokémon in any way you like. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: This seems to be the Iron Serpent mentioned in an old book. The Iron Serpent is said to have turned the land to ash with its lightning.

data.name: Miraidon ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Repulsion Bolt
attacks.text: If your opponent's Active Pokémon already has any damage counters on it, this attack does 100 more damage.

attacks.name: Cyber Drive
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't use Cyber Drive.

data.name: Lickilicky

attacks.name: Body Slam
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Tonguenado
attacks.text: Flip 4 coins. This attack does 70 damage for each heads.

data.flavorText: Lickilicky's strange tongue can stretch to many times the length of its body. No one has figured out how Lickilicky's tongue can stretch so far.

data.name: Hoothoot

attacks.name: Silent Wing
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand.

data.flavorText: It always stands on one foot. It changes feet so fast, the movement can rarely be seen.

data.name: Noctowl

attacks.name: Talon Hunt
attacks.text: You may search your deck for up to 2 cards and put them into your hand. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: Its eyes are specially developed to enable it to see clearly even in murky darkness and minimal light.

data.name: Dudunsparce

abilities.name: Run Away Draw
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may draw 3 cards. If you drew any cards in this way, shuffle this Pokémon and all attached cards into your deck.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon uses its hard tail to make its nest by boring holes into bedrock deep underground. The nest can reach lengths of over six miles.

data.name: Dunsparce

attacks.name: Dig
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from and effects of attacks done to this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It creates mazes in dark locations. When spotted, it flees into the ground by digging with its tail.

data.name: Skitty

attacks.name: Call for Family
attacks.text: Search your deck for a Basic Pokémon and put it onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: It can't stop itself from chasing moving things, and it runs in a circle, chasing its own tail.

data.name: Delcatty

attacks.name: Tail Trickery
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Confused.

attacks.name: Energy Blender
attacks.text: You may move any amount of Energy from your Pokémon to your other Pokémon in any way you like.

data.flavorText: It dislikes dirty places. It often searches for a comfortable place in which to groom itself.

data.name: Chatot

attacks.name: A Cappella
attacks.text: Search your deck for up to 3 Basic Pokémon and put them onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: It mimics the cries of other Pokémon to trick them into thinking it's one of them. This way they won't attack it.

data.name: Pidove

abilities.name: Emergency Evolution
abilities.text: Once during your turn, if this Pokémon's remaining HP is 30 or less, you may search your deck for an Unfezant or Unfezant ex and put it onto this Pidove to evolve it. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: Where people go, these Pokémon follow. If you're scattering food for them, be careful— several hundred of them can gather at once.

data.name: Tranquill

attacks.name: Jet Wing
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.flavorText: It can fly moderately quickly. No matter how far it travels, it can always find its way back to its master and its nest.

data.name: Unfezant

attacks.name: Opposing Winds
attacks.text: You may put 2 Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon into their hand.

attacks.name: Boundless Power
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.flavorText: Unfezant are exceptional fliers. The females are known for their stamina, while the males outclass them in terms of speed.

data.name: Minccino

attacks.name: Cleaning Up
attacks.text: Discard up to 2 Pokémon Tools from your opponent's Pokémon.

data.flavorText: The way it brushes away grime with its tail can be helpful when cleaning. But its focus on spotlessness can make cleaning more of a hassle.

data.name: Drampa

attacks.name: Raging Cannon
attacks.text: If all of your Benched Pokémon have at least 1 damage counter on them, this attack does 120 more damage.

data.flavorText: The mountains it calls home are nearly two miles in height. On rare occasions, it descends to play with the children living in the towns below.

data.name: Cinccino

attacks.name: Special Roll
attacks.text: This attack does 70 damage for each Special Energy card attached to this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Its body secretes oil that this Pokémon spreads over its nest as a coating to protect it from dust. Cinccino won't tolerate even a speck of the stuff.

data.name: Iron Jugulis

abilities.name: Automated Combat
abilities.text: If this Pokémon is in the Active Spot and is damaged by an attack from your opponent's Pokémon (even if this Pokémon is Knocked Out), put 3 damage counters on the Attacking Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It's possible that Iron Jugulis, an object described in an old book, may actually be this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: A Pokémon that was feared as a forest guardian. It can read the foe's mind and take preemptive action.

data.name: Grotle

data.flavorText: It lives along water in forests. In the daytime, it leaves the forest to sunbathe its treed shell.

data.name: Deerling

attacks.name: Leaf Litter Tackle
attacks.text: Discard a Grass Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Deerling have different scents depending on the season. In this form, Deerling have a softly sweet scent that lingers in the nose.

data.name: Sawsbuck

abilities.name: Changing Seasons
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may search your deck for a Stadium card, reveal it, and put it into your hand. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: Sawsbuck in their Autumn Form are known for having very short tempers. The males fight each other incessantly.

data.name: Litten

attacks.name: Fake Out
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

data.flavorText: It spends even the smallest amount of downtime grooming its fur with its tongue. Loose fur gathers in its stomach and serves as fuel for fiery moves.

data.name: Snom

attacks.name: Powder Snow
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

data.flavorText: It eats snow that has accumulated on the ground. It prefers soft, freshly fallen snow, so it will eat its way up a mountain, aiming for the peak.

data.name: Charjabug
data.flavorText: While its durable shell protects it from attacks, Charjabug strikes at enemies with jolts of electricity discharged from the tips of its jaws.

data.name: Bronzor

attacks.name: Mirror Attack
attacks.text: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is a Psychic Pokémon, this attack does 30 more damage.

data.flavorText: Ancient people believed that the pattern on Bronzor's back contained a mysterious power.

data.name: Reuniclus

attacks.name: Summoning Gate
attacks.text: Look at the top 8 cards of your deck. You may put any number of Pokémon you find there onto your Bench. Shuffle the other cards back into your deck.

attacks.name: Brain Shake
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Confused.

data.flavorText: While it could use its psychic abilities in battle, this Pokémon prefers to swing its powerful arms around to beat opponents into submission.

data.name: Cutiefly

attacks.name: Mini Drain
attacks.text: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Nectar and pollen are its favorite fare. You can find Cutiefly hovering around Gossifleur, trying to get some of Gossifleur's pollen.

data.name: Relicanth

abilities.name: Memory Dive
abilities.text: Each of your evolved Pokémon can use any attack from its previous Evolutions. (You still need the necessary Energy to use each attack.)

data.flavorText: Rock-hard scales and oil-filled swim bladders allow this Pokémon to survive the intense water pressure of the deep sea.

data.name: Excadrill

attacks.name: Wild Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 50 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: It's not uncommon for tunnels that appear to have formed naturally to actually be a result of Excadrill's rampant digging.

data.name: Mudsdale

attacks.name: Mud Stock

attacks.name: High Horsepower
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 40 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon has been treasured not just for its physical labor but also because it produces high-quality mud used for making pottery.

data.name: Arbok

attacks.name: Panic Poison
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Burned, Confused, and Poisoned.

data.flavorText: The pattern on its belly appears to be a frightening face. Weak foes will flee just at the sight of the pattern.

data.name: Gastly

attacks.name: Mysterious Beam
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, discard an Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It wraps its opponent in its gas-like body, slowly weakening its prey by poisoning it through the skin.

attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon's Meteor Mash attack does 60 more damage (before applying Weakness and Resistance).

attacks.name: Luster Blast
attacks.text: Discard 2 Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Because the magnetic powers of these Pokémon get stronger in freezing temperatures, Metagross living on snowy mountains are full of energy.

data.name: Meltan
data.flavorText: It dissolves and eats metal. Circulating liquid metal within its body is how it generates energy.

data.name: Lickitung

attacks.name: Tongue Pull
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand. Put up to 2 Basic Pokémon you find there onto your opponent's Bench.

data.flavorText: If this Pokémon's sticky saliva gets on you and you don't clean it off, an intense itch will set in. The itch won't go away, either.

data.name: Chatot

attacks.name: A Cappella
attacks.text: Search your deck for up to 3 Basic Pokémon and put them onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: It mimics the cries of other Pokémon to trick them into thinking it's one of them. This way they won't attack it.

data.name: Minccino

attacks.name: Cleaning Up
attacks.text: Discard up to 2 Pokémon Tools from your opponent's Pokémon.

data.flavorText: The way it brushes away grime with its tail can be helpful when cleaning. But its focus on spotlessness can make cleaning more of a hassle.

data.name: Cinccino

attacks.name: Special Roll
attacks.text: This attack does 70 damage for each Special Energy card attached to this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Its body secretes oil that this Pokémon spreads over its nest as a coating to protect it from dust. Cinccino won't tolerate even a speck of the stuff.

data.name: Drampa

attacks.name: Raging Cannon
attacks.text: If all of your Benched Pokémon have at least 1 damage counter on them, this attack does 120 more damage.

data.flavorText: The mountains it calls home are nearly two miles in height. On rare occasions, it descends to play with the children living in the towns below.

data.flavorText: Because of its unusual, starlike silhouette, people believe that it came here on a meteor.

data.name: Carvanha

data.name: Volbeat

attacks.name: Quick Sign
attacks.text: If you go first, you can use this attack during your first turn. Search your deck for up to 2 Basic Pokémon and put them onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

attacks.name: Coordinated Strike
attacks.text: If Illumise is on your Bench, this attack does 60 more damage.

data.flavorText: It flashes the light on its rear to communicate with other Volbeat. It loves the sweet aroma given off by Illumise.

data.name: Illumise

attacks.name: Slowing Perfume
attacks.text: You can use this attack only if you go second, and only during your first turn. Shuffle 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon and all attached cards into their deck.

data.flavorText: It guides Volbeat to draw signs in the night sky. There are scholars who research the meaning of these signs.

data.name: Leafeon

attacks.name: Leaflet Blessings
attacks.text: Attach a Basic Grass Energy card from your hand to 1 of your Benched Pokémon. If you do, heal all damage from that Pokémon.

data.flavorText: The younger they are, the more they smell like fresh grass. With age, their fragrance takes on the odor of fallen leaves.

data.name: Phantump

attacks.name: Leech Seed
attacks.text: Heal 20 damage from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon came to be when the spirit of a deceased child possessed a tree stump. It now wanders the forest searching for friends.

data.name: Trevenant

attacks.name: Giga Drain
attacks.text: Heal from this Pokémon the same amount of damage you did to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Trevenant is very kind to Pokémon living in the forest. It doesn't even care if these Pokémon take up residence in the greenery on its head.

data.name: Rillaboom

attacks.name: Drum Beating
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, attacks used by the Defending Pokémon cost Colorless more, and its Retreat Cost is Colorless more.

attacks.name: Wood Hammer
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 50 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: By drumming, it taps into the power of its special tree stump. The roots of the stump follow its direction in battle.

data.name: Dipplin

abilities.name: Festival Lead
abilities.text: If Festival Grounds is in play, this Pokémon may use an attack it has twice. If the first attack Knocks Out your opponent's Active Pokémon, you may attack again after your opponent chooses a new Active Pokémon.

attacks.name: Do the Wave
attacks.text: This attack does 20 damage for each of your Benched Pokémon.

data.flavorText: The head sticking out belongs to the fore-wyrm, while the tail belongs to the core-wyrm. The two share one apple and help each other out.

data.name: Sinistcha ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Re-Brew
attacks.text: Put 2 damage counters on 1 of your opponent's Pokémon for each Basic Grass Energy card in your discard pile. Then, shuffle those Energy cards into your deck.

attacks.name: Matcha Splash
attacks.text: Heal 30 damage from each of your Pokémon.

data.name: Grookey
data.flavorText: When it uses its special stick to strike up a beat, the sound waves produced carry revitalizing energy to the plants and flowers in the area.

data.name: Thwackey

abilities.name: Boom Boom Groove
abilities.text: Once during your turn, if your Active Pokémon has the Festival Lead Ability, you may search your deck for a card and put it into your hand. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: The faster a Thwackey can beat out a rhythm with its two sticks, the more respect it wins from its peers.

data.name: Applin

attacks.name: Tumbling Attack
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 more damage.

data.flavorText: Applin lives inside an apple. When an Applin is separated from its apple, its body loses moisture and the Pokémon grows weak.

data.name: Iron Leaves

attacks.name: Recovery Net
attacks.text: Put up to 2 Pokémon from your discard pile into your hand.

attacks.name: Avenging Edge
attacks.text: If any of your Pokémon were Knocked Out by damage from an attack during your opponent's last turn, this attack does 60 more damage.

data.flavorText: According to the few eyewitness accounts that exist, it used its shining blades to julienne large trees and boulders.

data.name: Poltchageist

abilities.name: Storehouse Hideaway
abilities.text: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage from and effects of attacks from your opponent's Pokémon done to this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Poltchageist looks like a regional form of Sinistea, but it was recently discovered that the two Pokémon are entirely unrelated.

data.name: Poltchageist

attacks.name: Tea Server
attacks.text: Put a Basic Grass Energy card from your discard pile into your hand.

attacks.name: Surprise Attack
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

data.flavorText: Poltchageist looks like a regional form of Sinistea, but it was recently discovered that the two Pokémon are entirely unrelated.

data.name: Sinistcha

attacks.name: Cursed Drop
attacks.text: Put 4 damage counters on your opponent's Pokémon in any way you like.

attacks.name: Spill the Tea
attacks.text: Discard up to 3 Grass Energy cards from your Pokémon. This attack does 70 damage for each card you discarded in this way.

data.flavorText: It prefers cool, dark places, such as the back of a shelf or the space beneath a home's floorboards. It wanders in search of prey after sunset.

data.name: Teal Mask Ogerpon

attacks.name: Mountain Stroll
attacks.text: Search your deck for up to 2 Basic Energy cards, reveal them, and put them into your hand. Then, shuffle your deck.

attacks.name: Ogre Comeback
attacks.text: This attack does 20 more damage for each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

data.flavorText: This mischief-loving Pokémon is full of curiosity. It battles by drawing out the type-based energy contained within its masks.

rules: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).

abilities.name: Teal Dance
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may attach a Basic Grass Energy card from your hand to this Pokémon. If you attached Energy to a Pokémon in this way, draw a card.

attacks.name: Myriad Leaf Shower
attacks.text: This attack does 30 more damage for each Energy attached to both Active Pokémon.

data.name: Vulpix
data.flavorText: As its body grows larger, its six warm tails become more beautiful, with a more luxurious coat of fur.

data.name: Ninetales

attacks.name: Eerie Glow
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Burned and Confused.

data.flavorText: It has nine long tails and fur that gleams gold. It is said to live for 1,000 years.

data.name: Slugma

attacks.name: Hot Magma
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Burned.

data.flavorText: It's said that in ancient times, when volcanoes were more active, there were many more Slugma than there are now.

data.name: Magcargo ex
rules: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).
Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.
Tera: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).

attacks.name: Hot Magma
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Burned.

attacks.name: Ground Burn
attacks.text: Discard the top card of each player's deck. This attack does 140 more damage for each Energy card discarded in this way.

data.name: Torkoal

attacks.name: Ramming Shell
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes 30 less damage from attacks (after applying Weakness and Resistance).

attacks.name: Fire Spin
attacks.text: Discard 2 Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Coal is the source of Torkoal's energy. Large amounts of coal can be found in the mountains where they live.

data.name: Chimchar

attacks.name: Firebreathing
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 more damage.

data.flavorText: Its fiery rear end is fueled by gas made in its belly. Even rain can't extinguish the fire.

data.name: Monferno

attacks.name: Heat Blow
attacks.text: Discard an Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It skillfully controls the intensity of the fire on its tail to keep its foes at an ideal distance.

data.name: Infernape

abilities.name: Pyro Dance
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may attach a Basic Fire Energy card, a Basic Fighting Energy card, or 1 of each from your hand to your Pokémon in any way you like.

attacks.name: Scorching Fire
attacks.text: Discard an Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Its crown of fire is indicative of its fiery nature. It is beaten by none in terms of quickness.

data.name: Darumaka

attacks.name: Fire Tackle
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: It derives its power from fire burning inside its body. If the fire dwindles, this Pokémon will immediately fall asleep.

data.name: Darmanitan

attacks.name: Inferno Onrush
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 70 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: The thick arms of this hot-blooded Pokémon can deliver punches capable of obliterating a dump truck.

data.name: Litwick

attacks.name: Call for Family
attacks.text: Search your deck for a Basic Pokémon and put it onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: While shining a light and pretending to be a guide, it leeches off the life-force of any who follow it.

data.name: Lampent

attacks.name: Burn It All Up
attacks.text: Discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: The spirits it absorbs fuel its baleful fire. It hangs around hospitals waiting for people to pass on.

data.name: Chandelure

abilities.name: Alluring Light
abilities.text: Once during your turn, you may have each player draw a card.

attacks.name: Mind Ruler
attacks.text: This attack does 30 damage for each card in your opponent's hand.

data.flavorText: It absorbs spirits, which it then burns. By waving the flames on its arms, it puts its foes into a hypnotic trance.

data.name: Chi-Yu

attacks.name: Allure
attacks.text: Draw 2 cards.

attacks.name: Ground Melter
attacks.text: If a Stadium is in play, this attack does 60 more damage. Then, discard that Stadium.

data.flavorText: The envy accumulated within curved beads that sparked multiple conflicts has clad itself in fire and become a Pokémon.

data.name: Hearthflame Mask Ogerpon ex
rules: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).
Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.
Tera: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).

attacks.name: Wrathful Hearth
attacks.text: This attack does 20 damage for each damage counter on this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Dynamic Blaze
attacks.text: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is an Evolution Pokémon, this attack does 140 more damage, and discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

data.name: Poliwag

attacks.name: Tail Rap
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 20 damage for each heads.

data.flavorText: Its legs are newly grown, and it can't walk very well. It seems to prefer swimming through the water instead.

data.name: Poliwhirl

attacks.name: Hypnosis
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

attacks.name: Double Slap
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 30 damage for each heads.

data.flavorText: Its skin is moist all over its body. The skin on its belly spiral also feels smooth.

data.name: Poliwrath

attacks.name: Hypnosis
attacks.text: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

attacks.name: Jumping Uppercut
attacks.text: You may do 120 more damage. If you do, shuffle this Pokémon and all attached cards into your deck.

data.flavorText: It can use its well-developed arms and legs to run on the surface of the water for a split second.

data.name: Goldeen

abilities.name: Festival Lead
abilities.text: If Festival Grounds is in play, this Pokémon may use an attack it has twice. If the first attack Knocks Out your opponent's Active Pokémon, you may attack again after your opponent chooses a new Active Pokémon.

attacks.name: Whirlpool
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, discard an Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: Its dorsal, pectoral, and tail fins wave elegantly in water. That is why it is known as the Water Dancer.

data.name: Seaking

attacks.name: Peck Off
attacks.text: Before doing damage, discard all Pokémon Tools from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: In autumn, its body becomes more fatty in preparing to propose to a mate. It takes on beautiful colors.

data.name: Jynx

attacks.name: Inviting Kiss
attacks.text: Search your deck for a Basic Pokémon and put it onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck. If you put any Pokémon onto your Bench in this way, move an Energy from this Pokémon to the new Benched Pokémon.

data.flavorText: In certain parts of Galar, Jynx was once feared and worshiped as the Queen of Ice.

data.name: Corphish
data.flavorText: It can live in impure water, where it doesn't need to compete with other water Pokémon for food, so its numbers have steadily increased.

data.name: Crawdaunt

attacks.name: Snip Snip
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. For each heads, discard the top card of your opponent's deck.

attacks.name: Rampaging Hammer
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.flavorText: A rough customer that wildly flails its giant claws. It is said to be extremely hard to raise.

data.name: Feebas

attacks.name: Flail
attacks.text: This attack does 10 damage for each damage counter on this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It is the shabbiest Pokémon of all. It forms schools and lives at the bottom of rivers that teem with plant life.

data.name: Milotic

abilities.name: Mentally Calm
abilities.text: Your opponent's Pokémon in play and all attached cards can't be put into your opponent's hand.

data.flavorText: It lives at the bottom of clear lakes. In times of war, it shows itself, which soothes people's minds and hearts.

data.name: Snorunt

attacks.name: Astonish
attacks.text: Choose a random card from your opponent's hand. Your opponent reveals that card and shuffles it into their deck.

data.flavorText: It is said that a home visited by a Snorunt will prosper. It can withstand cold of −150 degrees Fahrenheit.

data.name: Glalie

attacks.name: Damage Beat
attacks.text: This attack does 20 damage for each damage counter on your opponent's Active Pokémon.

attacks.name: Crazy Headbutt
attacks.text: Discard an Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It prevents prey from escaping by instantaneously freezing moisture in the air.

data.name: Froslass

abilities.name: Freezing Shroud
abilities.text: During Pokémon Checkup, put 1 damage counter on each Pokémon that has an Ability (both yours and your opponent's), except any Froslass.

data.flavorText: It freezes prey by blowing its −58 degree Fahrenheit breath. It is said to then secretly display its prey.

data.name: Froakie

attacks.name: Flock
attacks.text: Search your deck for up to 2 Froakie and put them onto your Bench. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: It secretes flexible bubbles from its chest and back. The bubbles reduce the damage it would otherwise take when attacked.

data.name: Frogadier

attacks.name: Numbing Water
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

data.flavorText: It can throw bubble-covered pebbles with precise control, hitting empty cans up to a hundred feet away.

data.name: Glaceon

attacks.name: Permeating Chill
attacks.text: At the end of your opponent's next turn, put 9 damage counters on the Defending Pokémon.

data.flavorText: It lowers its body heat to freeze its fur. The hairs then become like needles it can fire.

data.name: Phione

attacks.name: Beckon
attacks.text: Put a Supporter card from your discard pile into your hand.

attacks.name: Energy Press
attacks.text: This attack does 20 damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

data.flavorText: When the water warms, they inflate the flotation sac on their heads and drift languidly on the sea in packs.

data.name: Cramorant

attacks.name: Spit Shot
attacks.text: Discard all Energy from this Pokémon. This attack does 120 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon. (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

data.flavorText: It's an incredibly poor learner because it uses the bare minimum amount of energy for its brain. It focuses on battling instead.

data.name: Iron Bundle

attacks.name: Interjet
attacks.text: Switch this Pokémon with 1 of your Benched Pokémon. If you do, switch out your opponent's Active Pokémon to the Bench. (Your opponent chooses the new Active Pokémon.)

data.flavorText: It resembles a mysterious object mentioned in an old book. There are only two reported sightings of this Pokémon.

data.name: Finizen

attacks.name: Aqua Slash
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.flavorText: Its water ring is made from seawater mixed with a sticky fluid that Finizen secretes from its blowhole.

data.name: Palafin

abilities.name: Zero to Hero
abilities.text: Once during your turn, when this Pokémon moves from the Active Spot to the Bench, you may search your deck for a Palafin ex and switch it with this Pokémon. Any attached cards, damage counters, Special Conditions, turns in play, and any other effects remain on the new Pokémon. If you switched a Pokémon in this way, put this card into your deck. Then, shuffle your deck.

data.flavorText: Its physical capabilities are no different than a Finizen's, but when its allies are in danger, it transforms and powers itself up.

data.name: Palafin ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

abilities.name: Hero's Spirit
abilities.text: Put this Pokémon into play only with the effect of Palafin's Zero to Hero Ability.

attacks.name: Giga Impact
attacks.text: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

data.name: Walking Wake

attacks.name: Aurora Gain
attacks.text: Heal 20 damage from this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Undulating Slice
attacks.text: Put up to 9 damage counters on this Pokémon. This attack does 20 damage for each damage counter you placed in this way.

data.flavorText: This ferocious creature is shrouded in mystery. It's named after an aquatic monster mentioned in an old expedition journal.

data.name: Wellspring Mask Ogerpon ex
rules: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).
Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.
Tera: As long as this Pokémon is on your Bench, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon by attacks (both yours and your opponent's).

attacks.name: Sob
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, the Defending Pokémon can't retreat.

attacks.name: Torrential Pump
attacks.text: You may shuffle 3 Energy attached to this Pokémon into your deck. If you do, this attack also does 120 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon. (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

data.name: Zapdos

attacks.name: Thunder Wave
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Thunderbolt
attacks.text: Discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

data.flavorText: This Pokémon has complete control over electricity. There are tales of Zapdos nesting in the dark depths of pitch-black thunderclouds.

data.name: Shinx

attacks.name: Curiosity
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand.

data.flavorText: The extension and contraction of its muscles generates electricity. Its fur glows when it's in trouble.

data.name: Luxio

attacks.name: Big Bite
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, the Defending Pokémon can't retreat.

data.flavorText: By gathering their tails together, they collectively generate powerful electricity from their claws.

data.name: Emolga

attacks.name: Sky Wave
attacks.text: This attack also does 10 damage to each Benched Pokémon (both yours and your opponent's). (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

data.flavorText: As Emolga flutters through the air, it crackles with electricity. This Pokémon is cute, but it can cause a lot of trouble.

data.name: Luxray ex
rules: Pokémon ex rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent takes 2 Prize cards.

attacks.name: Piercing Gaze
attacks.text: Your opponent reveals their hand. Discard a card you find there.

attacks.name: Volt Strike
attacks.text: Discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

data.name: Helioptile

attacks.name: Collect
attacks.text: Draw a card.

data.flavorText: When spread, the frills on its head act like solar panels, generating the power behind this Pokémon's electric moves.

data.name: Heliolisk

attacks.name: Wild Charge
attacks.text: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

data.flavorText: A now-vanished desert culture treasured these Pokémon. Appropriately, when Heliolisk came to the Galar region, treasure came with them.
